{"key":"processedPost-15739048","value":{"id":15739048,"first":15738159,"last":27305059,"when":1327967615,"utime":"01/31/12 01:53 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>les moore said:</b><br /><br />I use minimal airholes in the terrarium, two x 1/8\".<br /><br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-005/795494026-terrarium_rs.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/12-005/795494026-thumb_terrarium_rs.jpg\"></a><br /></blockquote><br /><br />It's apparent without you even saying it that you don't have enough fresh air.<br /><br />Those poor mushrooms.&nbsp; That's mycelium abuse.&nbsp; Anytime you see fat or long stems and tiny, malformed caps, you're suffering from a major lack of fresh air.<br /><br />You see, it's not about humidity.&nbsp; Anyone can seal up a tub and get 99%.&nbsp; The trick to being a good mushroom grower is learning how to give a constantly circulating fresh air supply, <i>and still have 99% humidity.</i>&nbsp; That's why so many of us use shotgun terrariums with perlite.<br />RR","title":"Re: Humidity - Perlite not necessary - the indoor pool method","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}